# FamilyVault

## What This Project Is
A private, family-owned document vault PWA (Vue 3 + Capacitor) backed by AWS. Documents are uploaded, auto-classified by Textract + Claude, and retrievable via natural language search. Human confirmation is required before any document is saved.

## Stack

| Layer | Tech |
|-------|------|
| Frontend | Vue 3 + Vite + TailwindCSS + Pinia |
| Native shell | Capacitor (Android APK / iOS TestFlight) |
| Auth | AWS Cognito User Pools (Amplify SDK) |
| API | AWS API Gateway HTTP API + Cognito JWT Authorizer |
| Compute | AWS Lambda (Node.js 20 + TypeScript) |
| Database | DynamoDB single-table (`familyvault`) |
| File storage | S3 (presigned URLs only, SSE-S3 encrypted) |
| OCR | AWS Textract (sync for images, async+SNS for PDFs) |
| AI | Anthropic Claude Sonnet 4 (classification + search slot extraction) |
| IaC | AWS CDK (TypeScript) |
| Build | npm workspaces — `app/`, `lambdas/`, `infra/` |

## Project Structure

```
family-vault/
├── app/          — Vue 3 + Vite PWA (Capacitor)
│   └── src/
│       ├── views/        — page-level components
│       ├── components/   — reusable UI components
│       ├── composables/  — Vue composables
│       ├── stores/       — Pinia stores
│       ├── services/     — API + AWS SDK calls
│       ├── router/       — Vue Router
│       └── types/        — shared TypeScript types
├── lambdas/      — Lambda functions (each is a workspace)
│   ├── health-check/
│   └── shared/   — shared Lambda utilities
├── infra/        — AWS CDK stack
│   ├── lib/
│   │   ├── familyvault-stack.ts   — main stack definition
│   │   └── constructs/            — CDK constructs
│   └── bin/
└── Requirements.md   — authoritative source of truth for all design decisions
```

## Architecture Decisions

- **Single DynamoDB table** with PK/SK pattern + 4 GSIs (person-index, category-index, status-index, expiry-index)
- **S3 key format:** `{vaultId}/raw/{versionId}.{ext}` — UUID-based, s3Key never returned to frontend
- **ocrText** encrypted before DynamoDB write (AWS Encryption SDK); only first 1500 chars sent to Claude
- **Tenant isolation:** every DynamoDB query scoped to `vaultId` from JWT `custom:vaultId` claim
- **No auto-save:** all AI suggestions require explicit human confirmation (PATCH /documents/{id}/confirm)
- **Presigned URLs only:** S3 bucket has Block Public Access; GET URLs valid 15 min, PUT URLs valid 5 min
- **Cognito roles:** `custom:role` = `owner` or `member`; only owners can delete docs, manage family/categories

## Patterns We Follow

- Lambda functions extract `vaultId` and `role` from JWT claims — never trust client-supplied tenant IDs
- Person matching uses 3-layer algorithm: exact → relationship synonym → Levenshtein ≤ 2 (see Requirements.md §5.6)
- Poor OCR (< 50 chars or avg confidence < 60%) skips Claude entirely; UI prompts manual entry
- Document statuses: `PENDING → CONFIRMED | DELETED`; version statuses: `PROCESSING → AWAITING_CONFIRMATION → CONFIRMED | SUPERSEDED | FAILED`
- Push notifications delivered via SNS → Web Push service worker

## Never Do

- Never return `s3Key` to the frontend — always generate a presigned URL instead
- Never commit `aws-exports.ts` (git-ignored; use `aws-exports.example.ts` as template)
- Never send more than 1500 chars of OCR text to Claude
- Never auto-confirm a document — user confirmation step is a core security/trust requirement
- Never use public S3 URLs

## Key File Locations

- `Requirements.md` — authoritative design doc (data model, API spec, all functional requirements)
- `app/src/aws-exports.ts` — Cognito + API config (git-ignored)
- `infra/lib/familyvault-stack.ts` — main CDK stack
- `infra/lib/constructs/` — CDK constructs per resource group
- `lambdas/shared/` — shared Lambda utilities (DynamoDB client, JWT helpers, etc.)

## Context Tools Available (ctx-engine)

- `ctx_budget` — check context window before large operations
- `ctx_store(path:)` — store files in local knowledge base
- `ctx_recall("query")` — retrieve stored content on demand
- `ctx_checkpoint(...)` — save session state before compaction
- `ctx_shrink(content:)` — compress large content in context
- `ctx_list()` — see what is stored
- `ctx_forget(ref:)` — remove stored content

## Session Workflow

### Starting A Task
When the user says to start a task or work on a feature:
1. Call ctx_start("task name") first — always, before writing any code
2. Read the spec and sub-tasks it returns
3. Start implementing the first sub-task

### During Building
After completing each sub-task from ctx_start output:
1. Call ctx_progress with updated pct and the completed item in done[]
2. Continue to next sub-task
3. Estimate pct based on sub-tasks: 1 of 5 done = 20%, 2 of 5 = 40% etc

### Finishing A Task
When all sub-tasks are done:
1. Call ctx_progress(pct: 100, done: ["all sub-task names"])
2. Tell the user the task is complete
3. Ask what to work on next or suggest: ctx_start("next task")

### Context Health
Call ctx_budget every 10 tool calls automatically.
If runway drops below 15 turns, warn the user immediately.
```

---

### What Happens After This

You say:
```
start working on upload-url Lambda
```

Claude Code:
1. Calls `ctx_start("upload-url Lambda")` — spec loaded, sub-tasks ready
2. Builds the handler skeleton
3. Calls `ctx_progress(pct: 17, done: ["handler skeleton and types"])` automatically
4. Builds presigned URL generation
5. Calls `ctx_progress(pct: 33, done: ["presigned S3 PUT URL generation"])` automatically
6. Continues until done
7. Calls `ctx_progress(pct: 100, done: [...])`
8. Reports back to you: "upload-url Lambda is done. Ready for create-document Lambda?"

You never touch `ctx_progress`. You never think about percentages. You just watch it build.

